<h2> The strongest shock from half a century
The one recorded tonight at the Ingv in the Flegrei Fields in Naples, interested by a new seismic swarm, is the strongest shock at least in the last 54 years in the area where a bradisism under the Vesuvian Observatory insists. Between 1970 and 1972, as the Civil Protection Department recalls, seismic swarms with low magnitude events, largely not warned by the population: about 2,600 shocks were recorded between February 28 and October 30, 1970, all under magnitude of 2.0. Another 'Gradisisism crisis' is documented between 1982 and 1984: from its beginning until the end of 1983 there were over 5,000 significant events.
&nbsp;
In 1984, the number of earthquakes of higher magnitude increased (in July there were shocks up to 4.1) culminated in what marked 3.8 on December 8. From that moment on, the seismicry fell to an end in 1985.
&nbsp;
The most recent times, on October 27, 1996, recorded a shock of magnitude 4.1.&nbsp;
<h2>Schools closed to Pozzuoli and Naples
"For precaution we closed the schools of the ninth and tenth municipality for the technical checks that will happen in the morning," says the mayor Gaetano Manfredi, with reference to Fuorigrotta, Agnano and Bagnoli. "All our technical structures are operational h24". At 11.30, Manfredi will be in Sala Giunta, a press point that will be broadcast live on the site and on the Facebook page of the Municipality.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The mayor of Pozzuoli, Gigi Manzoni, is also preparing an order to close the schools on Tuesday, so that we can carry out checks on the buildings. "I'm in contact with the Minister and the Campania Region," says the mayor on Fb, inviting citizens to report damage and difficulty to the numbers of Civil Protection and local police. "We are also meeting with national and regional civil protection to manage criticism."
&nbsp;
Also the mayor of Qualiano, Raffaele de Leonardis, has signed the order to close all schools in its commune, both public and private, "also to allow technicians to carry out the work of structural verification of school buildings".
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, the autonomous Volturno Eav-Ente, has suspended from 20 the railway service on the lines Cumana and Circumflegrea "to allow the appropriate checks to the infrastructure". "It's a growing phenomenon. We expected a more frequent sism. The magnitude has reached the highest level of the last 40 years", said to Rai News the director of the Vesuvian Observatory, the volcanologist Mauro Di Vito. "Tomorrow, we'll do new sea controls."

